{"commentv2": 1, "number": 28, "id": 502452, "nreplies": 0, "sticky": 0, "user": "vikey", "body": "Lore : An ancient servant of Malygos, Hand of Magic, Sapphiron was a blue dragon who lived with a powerful brood in Northrend by the Dragonblight, where he communed with the ancient spirits of the dead dragons. Sapphiron was magnificently powerful, and protected the lands of Northrend as best he could. Though Ner'zhul's malevolent influence defiled the Dragonblight, Sapphiron and his brood continued to guard his hoard of treasure from any and all intruders. \r\n\r\nSapphiron and his brood lived in relative peace until King Arthas, champion of the Lich King, was suddenly called back to Northrend to save his weakening master, Ner'zhul. After three weeks at sea, the Death Knight landed on the shores of Northrend near Sapphiron's frozen lair, and was greeted almost immediately by the Crypt Lord Anub'arak, King of Azjol-Nerub, another powerful servant of Ner'zhul. Anub'arak had sensed Sapphiron nearby and suggested to the young Death Knight that perhaps by equipping themselves with the ancient blue wyrm's treasures, he and Arthas might be better prepared for the perilous journey through the underground kingdom of Azjol-Nerub to Icecrown Glacier. Arthas agreed, and boldly journeyed into Sapphiron's lair with Anub'arak. \r\n\r\nThe two servants of the Lich King fought their way through Sapphiron's minions till they finally reached the great blue dragon himself. Sapphiron confronted the undead as they approached him. He found Arthas's honesty about killing him and stealing his treasure quite \"refreshing\". Sapphiron and his fellow dragons attacked with all their might, unleashing their strange, cold frost magics upon them. In the end, despite all odds, Arthas was victorious, and Sapphiron was defeated. As a final, clinching victory, however, Arthas used what remained of his dwindling necromatic power to recreate Sapphiron as a frost wyrm to serve the Scourge. \r\n\r\nSapphiron, now a mighty frost wyrm, assisted Arthas in destroying the Naga and Blood Elf forces blocking the passage to Azjol-Nerub. Sapphiron was called upon again to destroy the dwarves guarding the gates to Azjol-Nerub, but the great dragon was left outside of the tunnels, where he guarded it against all who would disturb his new master. \r\n\r\nSome years later the Scourge attacked once again and Sapphiron was sent with Kel'Thuzad to the Eastern Plaguelands to guard the Black Citadel Naxxramas. \r\n\r\nSapphiron's powers are significantly greater than those of the average Frost Wyrm. This could be because Arthas, the Lich King's champion, revived him personally, or it could be a reflection of Sapphiron's greater power in life, or it could be some combination of both. \r\n\r\nCommander Eligor Dawnbringer: \"Sapphiron. Once a noble blue dragon within the mountains of Northrend, Sapphiron was slain by Arthas during his campaign through the frozen north. Resurrected to serve him, Sapphiron guards Kel'Thuzad's lair eternally, awaiting those who would dare trespass upon his master.\" \r\n\r\nTaken from wowwiki", "date": "2008-12-10T18:05:29-06:00", "rating": 35, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}}
{"commentv2": 1, "number": 29, "id": 506576, "nreplies": 0, "sticky": 0, "user": "149749", "body": "Currently there is a situation during the fight that allows Blizzard to continue during the air phase. This can become extremely irritating because the raid needs to stay behind an ice block to avoid death, but at the same time a blizzard is WTF pwning everyone with nothing we can do. Originally, my group was very frustrated that luck was part of the boss fight. After reading comments here and watching videos, there a few solutions that you can use if this happens to be the case during the fight. One way is to just have your healers AoE heal you (really only a solution if you're overgeared for the instance). Another is to start the air phase at one side of the room, then run as fast as you can to the other side so that the blizzard will take awhile to catch up to you.  Finally, staying somewhat spread out not only makes it so that fewer people are hit by the ice bolt AoE but also forces the blizzard to keep switching targets so that it is only one one person instead of an entire group. Waiting to collapse only after the second ice bolt allows maximum distance between your group and the blizzard before he does his frost breath. Hopefully this helps anyone who is having similar problems. But yes, luck is somewhat part of this encounter. Welcome to the Malchezzar of Naxx :)", "date": "2008-12-12T20:42:41-06:00", "rating": 0, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "lastEdit": ["2008-12-13T14:08:05-06:00", 1, "149749"]}
